@mkedgt2 @DiannaConleyVO @ADHD_Alien @danidonovan Free association! We make the best random associations. Why can’t other people just understand that?!?

@ABCsofADHD Time for a new special interest/hyperfixation. It doesn’t have to be brand new; revisiting past ones can be great, too. There’s this burst of dopamine when you finish a big project, and then it dissipates and you need something new to jump into, so you keep getting that rush.

@after_semicolon @BipolarActually @bipolexplorer The other thing that could be happening is that you have ADHD, but until recently many of your symptoms were accommodated, or maybe demands are higher now.

@after_semicolon @BipolarActually @bipolexplorer So it may not be ADHD, but trauma. Trauma can cause similar symptoms. The bonus is that the things that typically help ADHD often help with similar problems in other disorders (and neurotypicals find them useful, too).
@after_semicolon @BipolarActually @bipolexplorer Processing is hard! I’m good with reading but auditory input is difficult. And so then because processing takes longer, comprehension is harder.

@marysunfan94 @ABCsofADHD Irritable.. like I get mad over tiny things that normally wouldn’t bother me. I think often depression can be worse if you also have ADHD, because there is a lot that happens due to ADHD that we blame ourselves for, and that supports the negative thoughts of depression.

@after_semicolon @ABCsofADHD Loads of books, lots of blogs! Actually ADHD has a Tumblr (actuallyadhd) and a web site (https://t.co/yrxlXd0M4k). Totally ADD is a good site, and @ADDitudeMag is a great resource! Actually ADHD has a reading list on a page at the site and on Tumblr, too.
@orbitingclown @ABCsofADHD I’ll have to get the links when I’m on my computer later but yes, we have lots of posts on the actuallyadhd Tumblr about school!
@messymermaid @ABCsofADHD I can’t DM you (it’s not coming up as an option) but you can e-mail actuallyadhd@gmail.com anytime.

@after_semicolon @ABCsofADHD One of my friends is medicated for both, so it can be done; you do have to be extra careful, though. BUT strategies that help with ADHD can be helpful no matter what. Meds can help, but there are other possibilities if meds aren’t an option.
@gallacher_jo @ABCsofADHD << to work, and you can’t miss a dose.

@gallacher_jo @ABCsofADHD I haven’t tried Vyvanse (Elvanse), but I can tell you that it’s an amphetamine-based medication (I take Dexedrine). Strattera I have taken, and I didn’t like it in the end. It worked okay, but it also made me depressed. It’s one that needs to build up in your system >>
@makermattevans @ABCsofADHD Depends on what “productive” means and how you’re failing to be that.
@after_semicolon @ABCsofADHD Push to be assessed for ADHD. The two are definitely different.

@orbitingclown @ABCsofADHD There are a bunch over on Tumblr. Some depends on how you’re doing school now, though. I’ve been doing distance ed and that takes some different strategies than in person. I can link you to applicable posts on Tumblr if you let me know the situation.
@jess40383932 @ABCsofADHD If you’re okay with them talking, you could authorize both to share notes and maybe come to a consensus.
@jess40383932 @ABCsofADHD That’s a common mix-up and it’s also a common combination.
@mombojom @ABCsofADHD I’m bad at cleaning but great at organizing! If you want help, just ask! I need specific examples, though.

@marysunfan94 @ABCsofADHD There can be differences. Mostly, though, I think executive dysfunction can get worse, and my experience is that I get really irritable when my depression isn’t under control.
@LauraKa95346415 @ABCsofADHD @ADHD_and_LD That’s a really common thing, particularly for women/people who present as female.
@messymermaid @ABCsofADHD If you guys need some help with strategies that might be useful, let me know. Practical advice and tips & tricks are my jam!

@ADHD_MRB @ABCsofADHD So first of all, if you’re trying to “curb ADHD behaviours” you’re approaching things the wrong way. What you need to do is look at what is happening and why it’s a problem, then why it’s happening in the first place. Then you start making changes to make it easy to stop.

@thephilosophyf1 I agree, particularly that passing exams shouldn’t be given as much importance as it has. I understand that it’s a way to measure learning, but there are way better ways to do that, especially since so much of teaching now is only about the exams.

Managing ADHD requires strategies
Assess the situation. What isn’t working?
Decide on one change. How can you adjust routines or environment?
Have a go. How does it help?
Do it again.
